Analyses

First well start with a mean only model, followed by a model including game-type only. Were going to use zero-centred weak regularizing priors throughout. Regularizing priors usually result in better out of sample fit, as simulated in section 7.3 of rethinking. As an added bonus, they also stop BRMs warning of insufficient MCMC samples.


Baseline <- brm(
  data = d, family = bernoulli,
  Played1 ~ 1,
  prior = c(prior(normal(0, 1), class = Intercept)),
  iter = 10000, warmup = 5000, cores = 4, chains = 4,
  #control = list(adapt_delta = .9),
  seed = 42,
  file = "fits/Baseline"
)

Baseline <- add_criterion(Baseline, criterion = c("loo", "waic")) 

GameType <- brm(
  data = d, family = bernoulli,
  Played1 ~ 0 + Game_Type,
  prior = c(prior(normal(0, 1), class = b)),
  iter = 10000, warmup = 5000, cores = 4, chains = 4,
  #control = list(adapt_delta = .9),
  seed = 42,
  file = "fits/GameType"
)

GameType <- add_criterion(GameType, criterion = c("loo", "waic"))

Lets briefly inspect the outputs with a quick coefficient plot.


GtPlot <- posterior_samples(GameType) %>% 
  select(starts_with("b_")) %>%
  inv_logit_scaled() %>%
   mcmc_intervals(prob = .5,
                 point_est = "mean")

GtDiffPlot <- posterior_samples(GameType) %>% 
  select(starts_with("b_")) %>%
  inv_logit_scaled() %>%
  mutate(Dif = b_Game_TypeHUNT - b_Game_TypeFORAGE) %>%
  select(Dif) %>%
   mcmc_intervals(prob = .5,
                 point_est = "mean")

As we can see, there are substantial differences between game types, and no overlap in distributions. The model including game type will almost certainly outperform the mean only model, but lets confirm that with a brief model selection

ms1 <- loo_compare(Baseline, GameType, criterion = "loo") %>%
  round(digits = 2) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  select(elpd_diff,se_diff) %>% 
  rownames_to_column() %>%
  arrange(rowname)
  
ms1 <- model_weights(Baseline, GameType, weights = "loo") %>% 
  round(digits = 2) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  rownames_to_column() %>%
  arrange(rowname) %>%
  column_to_rownames("rowname") %>%
  cbind(ms1) %>%
  rename(
    Weights = ".",
    "ELPD Difference" = elpd_diff,
    "SE Difference" = "se_diff"
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(`ELPD Difference`)) %>%
  select(-rowname)
  
ms1

People were far more likely to play the hunting than the gathering game. Well explore how this differed by sex and age soon. However, first we should look at our study conditions. We ran rounds with and without prizes, and we ran rounds with and without a cost to pay. These could be coded as two binary variables (prize = 0/1; pay = 0/1), or as an equivalent four factor variable. Ive chosen to do the latter (e.g.see McElreath, 2021, Chapter 11).

Lets start simply by examining condition-specific differences, with varying effects for game type.


CrGt <- brm(data = d,
              family = bernoulli,
              Played1 ~ 0 + Condition + (0 + Condition | Game_Type),
              prior = c(prior(normal(0, 1), class = b)
                        ,prior(exponential(1), class = sd, group = Game_Type)
                        ,prior(lkj(2), class = cor, group = Game_Type)),
              seed = 42,
              iter = 10000, warmup = 5000, chains = 4, cores = 4,
              control = list(adapt_delta = .99),
              #These options banish some error messages but takes a while to run. 
              #Consider adjusting if you're not using a fast CPU.
              file = "fits/CrGt",
          )

CrGt <- add_criterion(CrGt, criterion = c("loo", "waic"))

Youll see Ive used descriptive model names. I find these easier to work with than numbered models. Ive abbreviated condition to C, Game_Type to gt etc. Lower case r represents random (i.e.varying) effects.

Lets see if this model improves upon the previous model in a model selection

ms2 <- loo_compare(Baseline, GameType, CrGt, criterion = "loo") %>%
  round(digits = 2) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  select(elpd_diff,se_diff) %>%

    "SE Difference" = "se_diff"

It does, and substantially so. Lets inspect our fitted values.



nd <-  d %>% 
  distinct(Condition, Game_Type)

CrGtFit <- fitted(CrGt, newdata = nd, probs = c(.05,.95)) %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  bind_cols(nd) %>%
  unite(col = "new", c(Condition, Game_Type), sep = "_") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Estimate, y = new)) + geom_point() + geom_errorbar(aes(xmin = Q5, xmax = Q95),width=0, lwd = 1)

CrGtFit

As we can see the differences in popularity between the hunting and foraging game are preserved when we introduce game type. The hunting game is in every instance more popular than the gathering game.

We also see substantial differences between conditions.The no pay conditions were both greatly more popular than the pay conditions. The presence of a prize also increased the probability of playing except, unexpectedly, between the two paid hunting conditions. The jump from no pay no prize to pay prize is very large. However given that this condition had only one round, this is probably explicable by the fact that there was attrition between games. Well control for this soon.

But first, gender. As we know, our data are cross-classified by sex and game type. Lets introduce gender to the model as a grouping variable.


CrGtrS <- brm(data = d,
              family = bernoulli,
              Played1 ~ 0 + Condition + (0 + Condition | Game_Type) + (0 + Condition | sex),
              prior = c(prior(normal(0, 1), class = b)
                        ,prior(exponential(1), class = sd, group = Game_Type)
                        ,prior(lkj(2), class = cor, group = Game_Type)
                        ,prior(exponential(1), class = sd, group = sex)
                        ,prior(lkj(2), class = cor, group = sex)
                        ),
              seed = 42,
              iter = 10000, warmup = 5000, chains = 4, cores = 4,
              control = list(adapt_delta = .97),
              #These settings banish some error messages but the model takes a while to run. 
              #Consider adjusting if you're not using a fast CPU.
              file = "fits/CrGtrS",
          )

CrGtrS <- add_criterion(CrGtrS, criterion = c("loo", "waic"))

Lets see if this outperforms the previous models in a model selection

ms3 <- loo_compare(Baseline, GameType, CrGt, CrGtrS, criterion = "loo") %>%
  round(digits = 2) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  select(elpd_diff,se_diff) %>%

  arrange(rowname)

    Weights = ".",
    "ELPD Difference" = elpd_diff,
    "SE Difference" = "se_diff"
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(`ELPD Difference`)) %>%
  select(-rowname)

Yes, including participant gender substantially improves the model.

CrGtrSFitM + CrGtrSFitF + plot_layout(ncol = 2)

As we can see, women almost universally were less inclined to play across conditions. The patterning of results is otherwise similar - the hunting game was more popular across genders. There were two notable sex differences. Women were substantially less likely to participate in the no pay no bracelet condition that were men, despite overlapping distributions for the no pay, bracelet condition. Also, contrary to expectations, men were more likely to pay to play in the pay no bracelet condition than the pay bracelet condition.

Were also interested in the impacts of age. Younger people potentially have more to gain by showing off. As were only interested in broad trends, rather than year-by-year changes, weve coded age as a binary variable using median age split. Lets see how it performs both on its own and alongside gender.


CrGtrA <- brm(data = d,
              family = bernoulli,
              Played1 ~ 0 + Condition + (0 + Condition | Game_Type) + (0 + Condition | AgeSplit),
              prior = c(prior(normal(0, 1), class = b)
                        ,prior(exponential(1), class = sd, group = Game_Type)
                        ,prior(lkj(2), class = cor, group = Game_Type)
                        ,prior(exponential(1), class = sd, group = AgeSplit)
                        ,prior(lkj(2), class = cor, group = AgeSplit)
                        ),
              seed = 42,
              iter = 10000, warmup = 5000, chains = 4, cores = 4,
              control = list(adapt_delta = .99),
              #This settings banish some error messages but takes a while to run. 
              #Consider adjusting if you're not using a fast CPU.
              file = "fits/CrGtrA",
          )

CrGtrA <- add_criterion(CrGtrA, criterion = c("loo", "waic"))


CrGtrSrA <- brm(data = d,
              family = bernoulli,
              Played1 ~ 0 + Condition + (0 + Condition | Game_Type) + (0 + Condition | sex) + (0 + Condition | AgeSplit),
              prior = c(prior(normal(0, 1), class = b)
                        ,prior(exponential(1), class = sd, group = Game_Type)
                        ,prior(lkj(2), class = cor, group = Game_Type)
                        ,prior(exponential(1), class = sd, group = sex)
                        ,prior(lkj(2), class = cor, group = sex)
                        ,prior(exponential(1), class = sd, group = AgeSplit)
                        ,prior(lkj(2), class = cor, group = AgeSplit)
                        ),
              seed = 42,
              iter = 10000, warmup = 5000, chains = 4, cores = 4,
              control = list(adapt_delta = .99),
              #This settings banish some error messages but takes a while to run. 
              #Consider adjusting if you're not using a fast CPU.
              file = "fits/CrGtrSrA",
          )

CrGtrSrA <- add_criterion(CrGtrSrA, criterion = c("loo", "waic"))

Lets see how these perform relative to the models excluding age in a model selection.



ms4 <- loo_compare(Baseline, GameType, CrGt, CrGtrS,CrGtrA,CrGtrSrA, criterion = "loo") %>%
  round(digits = 2) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  select(elpd_diff,se_diff) %>% 
  rownames_to_column() %>%
  arrange(rowname)
  
ms4 <- model_weights(Baseline, GameType, CrGt, CrGtrS,CrGtrA,CrGtrSrA, weights = "loo") %>% 
  round(digits = 2) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  rownames_to_column() %>%
  arrange(rowname) %>%
  column_to_rownames("rowname") %>%
  cbind(ms4) %>%
  rename(
    Weights = ".",
    "ELPD Difference" = elpd_diff,
    "SE Difference" = "se_diff"
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(`ELPD Difference`)) %>%
  select(-rowname) %>%
  relocate(Weights, .after = "SE Difference") %>% 
  mutate(
    Definition = c("0 + Condition + (0 + Condition | GameType) + (0 + Condition | Sex) + (0 + Condition | Age)"
                   ,"0 + Condition + (0 + Condition | GameType) + (0 + Condition | Sex)"
                   ,"0 + Condition + (0 + Condition | GameType) + (0 + Condition | Age)"
                   ,"0 + Condition + (0 + Condition | GameType)"
                   ,"0 + GameType"
                   , "1") 
    , .before = 1
  )
  
ms4

CrGtrAFitM + CrGtrAFitF

Ive stripped out figure legends here to save space, but in this figure predictions for men are profided on the left left, women on the right.

As we can see, younger individuals were almost universally more likely to play across genders and conditions. The sex and condition specific differences are largely preserved (men above women below). This is our full model, including all study predictor variables of interest. There are still a few potential experimental artefacts which we havent accounted for, and these are explored in the fourth analysis file. None of them substantial alter the findings presented here, however, so well report this model in the manuscript.

That being the case, well explore this model a little further in document three.
